    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#ferri1923"/>, p. 9, n. <citedRange>8a</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.137</citedRange></bibl>;
                    published again by <bibl>Morelli, <ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>218</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>, as if unpublished;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>021600</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2020b"/>, p. <citedRange>63</citedRange>, footnote 38</bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Hestia"><name nymRef="#Ἱστία">Ἱσ<supplied reason="lost">τ</supplied><unclear>ί</unclear>ας</name></persName>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <rdg resp="#ferri1923">Ἱσ<supplied reason="lost">τ</supplied>ίας</rdg>
                        <rdg resp="#SECir">Ἑ<supplied reason="lost">κ</supplied>άτας</rdg>
                    </app>
               </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Autel</supplied> d'Hestia.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altar</supplied> of Hestia.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altare</supplied> di Estia.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Known through a simple mention by Ferri, it belongs to the series of altars with compartments of the so-called '<foreign xml:lang="it">agorà degli dei</foreign>'.
                Neither illustration nor dimensions were given then.</p>
                <p>Morelli in <bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>218</citedRange></bibl> gave no illustration, but from localisation, dimensions and similarity with <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr021700</ref>, 
	              Dobias-Lalou could trace the stone, although she was unable to provide any useful image for <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/></bibl>. See also <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2020b"/></bibl>.</p>
	           <p>Morelli's different reading is due to the bad condition of the stone, worn out and covered by concretion. The first sigma being clear, Ferri's reading seems 
	           the better one.</p>
            </div></body>
